00:26:29.240 --> 00:26:30.890
Now, many people, when
they're gaining weight

00:26:30.890 --> 00:26:33.130
and having trouble
will say, "All right.

00:26:33.130 --> 00:26:34.720
I'm with you.

00:26:34.720 --> 00:26:36.020
I'm going to go online.

00:26:36.020 --> 00:26:39.220
I'm going to get the Atkins diet
and that's what I'm going to do."

00:26:39.220 --> 00:26:41.420
And let me caution you about that.

00:26:41.420 --> 00:26:46.680 position:56%
Um, these books have been very, very
popular because they say the reason

00:26:46.680 --> 00:26:49.620
that we're heavy is because
we're eating too much rice

00:26:49.620 --> 00:26:50.990
and too much bread
and too many potatoes

00:26:50.990 --> 00:26:52.290
and too many carbs in general.

00:26:52.290 --> 00:26:54.790
And if you stop eating all those
things, you'll lose weight.

00:26:54.790 --> 00:26:58.080
And that's true because carbs
are half of what we eat.

00:26:58.080 --> 00:27:01.450
And if you throw out all the
potatoes and all the bread

00:27:01.450 --> 00:27:02.980
and all the rice and all the
cookies and all the cakes

00:27:02.980 --> 00:27:06.560
and all the fruit,
you will lose weight.

00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:09.310
Unless you eat more of other things

00:27:09.310 --> 00:27:11.310
so that your calorie
intake doesn't fall,

00:27:11.310 --> 00:27:13.350
in which case you don't
lose any weight at all.

00:27:13.350 --> 00:27:15.020
There's a whole lot of
frustrated dieters out there.

00:27:15.020 --> 00:27:18.150
So, I'm going to suggest
that bread is not the issue.

00:27:18.150 --> 00:27:22.280
Um, so a big problem with
this kind of dieting is

00:27:22.280 --> 00:27:25.150
that these are the
foods that are left

00:27:25.150 --> 00:27:29.460
when you're leaving out,
uh, the healthy foods.

00:27:29.460 --> 00:27:32.690 position:56%
And so if you tuck into these
things and your calorie content ends

00:27:32.690 --> 00:27:35.190
up going up, you aren't going
to lose any weight whatsoever.

00:27:35.190 --> 00:27:36.770 position:56%
But even when people do lose weight,

00:27:36.770 --> 00:27:38.850
they very often end
up with heart disease.

00:27:38.850 --> 00:27:44.400
And this, uh, was sent to me by
a young man named Jody Gerand

00:27:44.400 --> 00:27:47.520
who said that, "I want to tell
people what happened to me."

00:27:47.520 --> 00:27:52.030
He happened to be in the hospital
and he had a scan of his heart

00:27:52.030 --> 00:27:53.370
for -- that he didn't really need.

00:27:53.370 --> 00:27:56.090
He didn't have heart disease,
but they did this scan as part

00:27:56.090 --> 00:27:59.930
of a special physical exam
that he -- that he had.

00:27:59.930 --> 00:28:02.210
And I'm not going to ask you
to read this, but bottom line,

00:28:02.210 --> 00:28:03.980
he had no heart disease whatsoever.

00:28:03.980 --> 00:28:05.280
He was fine.

00:28:05.280 --> 00:28:06.960
And he was just a little
bit overweight,

00:28:06.960 --> 00:28:08.750
less than 10 pounds overweight.

00:28:08.750 --> 00:28:14.020 position:56%
But low-carb dieting was such a fad,
he thought, "Let me do it that way."

00:28:14.020 --> 00:28:16.080
So he threw out all the bread
and he followed it very --

00:28:16.080 --> 00:28:17.920
you know, very religiously.

00:28:17.920 --> 00:28:23.040 position:56%
He was eating gravy and heavy cream,
but no bread, no rice, no potatoes.

00:28:23.040 --> 00:28:26.760
And one day he was
walking in New York

00:28:26.760 --> 00:28:29.910
and an elephant sat on his chest.

00:28:29.910 --> 00:28:31.210
He had crushing chest pain.

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:35.700
He went into the emergency room
and he was having a heart attack.

00:28:35.700 --> 00:28:39.950
And they did an angiogram and,
see, there's a little place

00:28:39.950 --> 00:28:42.440
where it's all white where it
should be a -- a good artery.

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:45.910
He had a 97% blockage in his heart.

00:28:45.910 --> 00:28:48.910
And his doctor said, "What
have you been doing?"

00:28:48.910 --> 00:28:51.500
And he told them what
he had been doing.

00:28:51.500 --> 00:28:54.300
And his diet was so high in
cholesterol and animal fat,

00:28:54.300 --> 00:28:56.530
it's just a recipe
for heart disease.

00:28:56.530 --> 00:29:00.080 position:56%
Now, normally, when you lose
weight, your cholesterol should fall

00:29:00.080 --> 00:29:01.930
and that often does happen.

00:29:01.930 --> 00:29:03.940
But on about 1/3 Atkins dieters,

00:29:03.940 --> 00:29:05.240
even though they may
be losing weight

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:07.230
because they're eating fewer
calories, their cholesterols go

00:29:07.230 --> 00:29:09.260
up sometimes just absolutely
through the roof.

00:29:09.260 --> 00:29:11.720
So he said, "Forget that,"
went on a plant based diet,

00:29:11.720 --> 00:29:13.680
has had no trouble
keeping a healthy weight,

00:29:13.680 --> 00:29:16.340
and his arteries opened up again.

00:29:16.340 --> 00:29:24.590
In Australia researchers found
something that shocked all of us

00:29:24.590 --> 00:29:27.740
who felt maybe we can
change our diet in mid-life

00:29:27.740 --> 00:29:29.400
and we're going to be OK.

00:29:29.400 --> 00:29:36.800
Um, they measured the thickness of
the artery wall, which you can do

00:29:36.800 --> 00:29:40.170
in an adult and you
can do it in a baby.

00:29:40.170 --> 00:29:43.740 position:56%
And if you look at, say, the carotid
artery, which goes up to your brain,

00:29:43.740 --> 00:29:46.420
and you do a simple
non-invasive test,

00:29:46.420 --> 00:29:49.810
you can see how thick
the artery wall is.

00:29:49.810 --> 00:29:56.250
And they brought and 23 women
and their brand new babies.

00:29:56.250 --> 00:29:58.340
Within the first week of
life, it turned out that

00:29:58.340 --> 00:30:01.930
if the mother was eating extra
food and she was overweight,

00:30:01.930 --> 00:30:07.900
her baby was already getting
arterial thickening in the womb

00:30:07.900 --> 00:30:10.230
that you can measure at birth.

00:30:10.230 --> 00:30:15.240
And then if those same foods are
then part of the family's culture,

00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:18.360
by the time that child is
18, he or she will have lost

00:30:18.360 --> 00:30:20.140
at least vertebral artery.

00:30:20.140 --> 00:30:23.970
And by the time the
child is in mid-life,

00:30:23.970 --> 00:30:27.420
virtually all of them will have
standard atherosclerotic heart

00:30:27.420 --> 00:30:31.560
disease, which we had thought
was just part of human biology.

00:30:31.560 --> 00:30:35.990
And we now know that it's related
to food, smoking, and other aspects

00:30:35.990 --> 00:30:39.050
of lifestyle that we can control.

00:30:39.050 --> 00:30:41.510
So let me shift gears
just a little bit.

00:30:41.510 --> 00:30:44.490
One of the big contributors
to heart risk is diabetes.

00:30:44.490 --> 00:30:45.990
And if you don't mind I'd
like to spend just a couple

00:30:45.990 --> 00:30:48.220
of minutes on -- on diabetes.

00:30:48.220 --> 00:30:50.320
Uh, because it's a
major contributor,

00:30:50.320 --> 00:30:53.030
not just to heart disease,
but many other issues.

00:30:53.030 --> 00:30:54.700
In 2003 the National Institutes

00:30:54.700 --> 00:30:58.300 position:56%
of Health gave our research team a
grant to test a plant based diet not

00:30:58.300 --> 00:31:00.830 position:56%
for heart disease, but for diabetes.

00:31:00.830 --> 00:31:03.750
And the idea was to do
a head-to-head test,

00:31:03.750 --> 00:31:06.880
a vegan diet versus what
we called an ADA diet,

00:31:06.880 --> 00:31:10.240
American Diabetes Association
diet that meant counting calories

00:31:10.240 --> 00:31:12.390
and limiting carbohydrate
and that kind of thing.

00:31:12.390 --> 00:31:13.930
Twenty-two week study.

00:31:13.930 --> 00:31:17.510
And the test that we use

00:31:17.510 --> 00:31:20.570
for measuring blood sugar
control is called A1C.

00:31:20.570 --> 00:31:23.440
If you have diabetes, you
know what I'm talking about.

00:31:23.440 --> 00:31:25.610
Hemoglobin A1C is a measure

00:31:25.610 --> 00:31:27.440
of how good your blood
sugar control has been

00:31:27.440 --> 00:31:30.110
for the preceding three
months or so.

00:31:30.110 --> 00:31:33.230
And it should be below seven.

00:31:33.230 --> 00:31:34.680
At least that's our target.

00:31:34.680 --> 00:31:38.310
But, at the start of the study,
our people were not below seven.

00:31:38.310 --> 00:31:39.940 position:56%
They were all hovering around eight.

00:31:39.940 --> 00:31:43.060
And the people on the ADA
diet, that's the red line,

00:31:43.060 --> 00:31:45.940
they had an OK drop
of about 0.4 points.

00:31:45.940 --> 00:31:47.240
That's good.

00:31:47.240 --> 00:31:49.410
But the blue line was
the vegan group.

00:31:49.410 --> 00:31:52.660
They had a drop in
absolute percentage terms

00:31:52.660 --> 00:31:56.350
of 1.2 absolute percentage
points, which was bigger

00:31:56.350 --> 00:32:01.290
than any oral diabetes medication
marketed just on average.

00:32:01.290 --> 00:32:02.590
And it was huge.

00:32:02.590 --> 00:32:05.250
And then we followed them
over a year and the people

00:32:05.250 --> 00:32:07.540
in the control group ended up
getting back to where they started.

00:32:07.540 --> 00:32:08.970
And the people in the vegan group,

00:32:08.970 --> 00:32:11.040
some of them didn't follow
it perfectly, but on average,

00:32:11.040 --> 00:32:14.760
they were still way better
than at the beginning.

00:32:14.760 --> 00:32:17.850
And we had some people where
their diabetes simply went away.

00:32:17.850 --> 00:32:19.960
And then we just looked
at their body weight.

00:32:19.960 --> 00:32:22.670 position:56%
And we found there wasn't a
dramatic difference between the two.

00:32:22.670 --> 00:32:25.350
The red line is the ADA
folks and they lost weight.

00:32:25.350 --> 00:32:26.650
And so did the vegans.

00:32:26.650 --> 00:32:28.300
The vegans lost a little
bit more weight.

00:32:28.300 --> 00:32:31.000
But the -- the important
thing here is

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.840
that the vegan group wasn't
trying to lose weight.

00:32:33.840 --> 00:32:36.630
They were free to eat as much
spaghetti as they wanted to.

00:32:36.630 --> 00:32:39.180
There was no calorie
limit whatsoever,

00:32:39.180 --> 00:32:41.800
but the red line was the people
on the ADA diet where they sit

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:45.030
down with a dietitian
who says, "All right.

00:32:45.030 --> 00:32:46.940
You're eating 1,800
calories a day now.

00:32:46.940 --> 00:32:48.280
Here's your menu.

00:32:48.280 --> 00:32:50.360
It adds up to 1,300."

00:32:50.360 --> 00:32:52.430
"Aren't I going to be hungry?"

00:32:52.430 --> 00:32:54.350
Yes. But it's calories
in, calories out.

00:32:54.350 --> 00:32:56.070
You got to cut your calories
if you're going to lose weight.

00:32:56.070 --> 00:32:58.720
"How long do I have
to stay on this?"

00:32:58.720 --> 00:33:02.690
"Until you reach your ideal
body weight, which is never."

00:33:02.690 --> 00:33:06.300
And the patient leaves
with this menu

00:33:06.300 --> 00:33:09.560
and this gets old by
about Wednesday.

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:11.460
And you're ready to eat the sofa.

00:33:11.460 --> 00:33:13.990
And then you start berating the
patient, "You're not compliant!

00:33:13.990 --> 00:33:15.290
You're noncompliant!"

00:33:15.290 --> 00:33:16.600
Who is going to be compliant

00:33:16.600 --> 00:33:20.100
with being hungry every
single day of their life?

00:33:20.100 --> 00:33:22.400
And instead, with the people
on the plant based diet,

00:33:22.400 --> 00:33:24.060
they were free to eat chili.

00:33:24.060 --> 00:33:26.330
It was just not meat
chili, it was bean chili.

00:33:26.330 --> 00:33:28.120
There's so much fiber
in it, it's filling.

00:33:28.120 --> 00:33:31.240
And you push away from
the table a little sooner

00:33:31.240 --> 00:33:33.750
so your calorie intake,
it actually does fall.

00:33:33.750 --> 00:33:35.620
But you're totally unaware of it.

00:33:35.620 --> 00:33:39.710 position:56%
Totally satisfied and the weight
loss is greater on that kind of diet

00:33:39.710 --> 00:33:42.830
that doesn't cause hunger at all
than on a person who's trying

00:33:42.830 --> 00:33:47.270
to muscle through it and use
discipline and wheel power.

00:33:47.270 --> 00:33:49.030
When we want to help our
patients comply with it,

00:33:49.030 --> 00:33:50.870
we don't use wheel power at all.

00:33:50.870 --> 00:33:52.330
You just set up a structure
that they can't fail.

00:33:52.330 --> 00:33:54.250
And they don't have to worry.

00:33:54.250 --> 00:33:56.300
Is this making sense?

00:33:56.300 --> 00:33:58.040
OK. All right.

00:33:58.040 --> 00:34:01.200
Oh, and LDL, low density
lipoprotein, drops like a stone.

00:34:01.200 --> 00:34:02.500
You're not eating any
animal fat at all.

00:34:02.500 --> 00:34:03.800
It always falls.

00:34:03.800 --> 00:34:05.450
OK. This is my most important
slide for anybody with diabetes.

00:34:05.450 --> 00:34:07.480
I want -- I want to just
walk you through this

00:34:07.480 --> 00:34:09.410
because I guarantee your
friends don't know about this

00:34:09.410 --> 00:34:14.060
and your doctor does
not know about this.

00:34:14.060 --> 00:34:17.100
Diabetes means there's too
much sugar in the blood.

00:34:17.100 --> 00:34:18.950
That sugar is glucose.

00:34:18.950 --> 00:34:20.250
And glucose is not bad.

00:34:20.250 --> 00:34:21.550
Glucose is good.

00:34:21.550 --> 00:34:22.850
Glucose powers your brain.

00:34:22.850 --> 00:34:25.020
It powers your muscles.

00:34:25.020 --> 00:34:28.050
The problem in diabetes is that
you've got glucose in your blood,

00:34:28.050 --> 00:34:30.520
not inside the cells
where it can do some good.

00:34:30.520 --> 00:34:32.930
It's building up in the
blood and you can test --

00:34:32.930 --> 00:34:34.510
your blood tests show it.

00:34:34.510 --> 00:34:37.160 position:56%
You think, "If it would only go into
my cells, I wouldn't have diabetes."

00:34:37.160 --> 00:34:39.430
And that's true.

00:34:39.430 --> 00:34:43.000
Researchers at Yale
University used a special kind

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:48.070
of test called MR spectroscopy
where they scanned people's muscles

00:34:48.070 --> 00:34:50.010
and their livers and
they found something

00:34:50.010 --> 00:34:52.780
that completely revolutionized
our approach to diabetes.

00:34:52.780 --> 00:34:55.210
This is a muscle cell.

00:34:55.210 --> 00:34:58.130
OK? And muscles are
where most of the glucose

00:34:58.130 --> 00:34:59.480
in the blood is trying to go.

00:34:59.480 --> 00:35:01.150
And so you've got glucose.

00:35:01.150 --> 00:35:02.450
It's there.

00:35:02.450 --> 00:35:03.850
Those little dots trying
to get into the cell.

00:35:03.850 --> 00:35:07.340
You've got insulin --
insulin's a hormone.

00:35:07.340 --> 00:35:08.810
It's like a key.

00:35:08.810 --> 00:35:10.720
It opens that cell up.

00:35:10.720 --> 00:35:12.800
OK? So the glucose
needs to get inside,

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:14.520
but you need the insulin to do it.

00:35:14.520 --> 00:35:16.850
So the insulin signals
these channels to open up.

00:35:16.850 --> 00:35:18.150
And there's the glucose.

00:35:18.150 --> 00:35:20.260
It's not going in now because
insulin let it in the cell.

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:24.570
But there's something
else in that cell.

00:35:24.570 --> 00:35:27.160
See those yellow globs?

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:28.810
That's fat.

00:35:28.810 --> 00:35:32.140
Fat droplets inside the cell.

00:35:32.140 --> 00:35:34.360
And they build up based
on what I've been eating.

00:35:34.360 --> 00:35:36.520
Doctors hate words like, "Fat."

00:35:36.520 --> 00:35:39.440
It's got one syllable,
three letters.

00:35:39.440 --> 00:35:43.290
So we refer to it as
intramyocellular lipid, but it's --

00:35:43.290 --> 00:35:47.720
it's fat inside -- intra- means
inside, myo- means muscle,

00:35:47.720 --> 00:35:52.050
cellular means cellular,
lipid means fat.

00:35:52.050 --> 00:35:54.410
If you eat -- this comes
from food that you're eating.

00:35:54.410 --> 00:35:58.140
So you eat chicken fat and it
goes inside the muscle cells

00:35:58.140 --> 00:36:00.860
with very little conversion
to anything else.

00:36:00.860 --> 00:36:04.560
You eat cheese fat or
dairy fat or fryer grease

00:36:04.560 --> 00:36:06.620 position:56%
or whatever, it's inside the muscle.

00:36:06.620 --> 00:36:11.970
And as it goes in there, it
stops insulin from working.

00:36:14.050 --> 00:36:16.870
The reason a person
develops diabetes is not

00:36:16.870 --> 00:36:20.450
because they were eating
rice or eating potatoes.

00:36:20.450 --> 00:36:22.210
It's because fat built
up inside the cell

00:36:22.210 --> 00:36:23.860
and it makes your insulin
no longer work.

00:36:23.860 --> 00:36:25.690
And if the insulin doesn't
work, the glucose builds

00:36:25.690 --> 00:36:28.010 position:56%
up in the blood and you can test it.

00:36:28.010 --> 00:36:31.540
And your doctor says, "You've got
too much glucose in your blood.

00:36:31.540 --> 00:36:33.860
You need to start medication."

00:36:33.860 --> 00:36:38.600
Well, diabetes is not
a metformin deficiency.

00:36:38.600 --> 00:36:42.480
All these drugs do is they try
to stimulate more insulin release

00:36:42.480 --> 00:36:44.250
or make the cell react more.

00:36:44.250 --> 00:36:48.000
And until the Yale researchers
scanned patients with diabetes

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:53.720 position:56%
and found fat inside their cells,
we weren't able to tackle the cause.

00:36:53.720 --> 00:36:55.460 position:56%
So why did our research participants

00:36:55.460 --> 00:36:57.320
who had diabetes do
better on a vegan diet?

00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:00.110
Because there's no animal
fat in the diet at all.

00:37:00.110 --> 00:37:03.160
And if you keep the
vegetable oils low,

00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:04.930
do you know what happens
inside that cell?

00:37:04.930 --> 00:37:06.530
The fat starts dissipating.

00:37:06.530 --> 00:37:07.860
The insulin starts working again.

00:37:07.860 --> 00:37:10.720
And you've got a shot of
getting rid of your diabetes

00:37:10.720 --> 00:37:14.680
or having it improve dramatically
and needing less medication,

00:37:14.680 --> 00:37:17.460
sometimes none at all, because
you're tackling the cause.

00:37:17.460 --> 00:37:20.230
OK? So if you know anybody who's
got diabetes and they're saying,

00:37:20.230 --> 00:37:22.950
"I'm not going to eat any
bread," take out a napkin

00:37:22.950 --> 00:37:26.610
and start drawing my cell and
showing the fat globs inside

00:37:26.610 --> 00:37:30.470
and that is your target, a low
fat vegan diet will cause diabetes

00:37:30.470 --> 00:37:31.810
to start turning around.

00:37:31.810 --> 00:37:33.110
Weight comes down.

00:37:33.110 --> 00:37:34.410
Cholesterol comes down.

00:37:34.410 --> 00:37:35.710
Blood sugars come down.

00:37:35.710 --> 00:37:37.010
In some cases they are never
going to know they had it.

00:37:37.010 --> 00:37:39.940
We, uh, did a study
recently with people

00:37:39.940 --> 00:37:43.490
who have late stage
diabetes where, as you know,

00:37:43.490 --> 00:37:44.790
diabetes attacks the eyes.

00:37:44.790 --> 00:37:47.960
It attacks the kidneys.

00:37:47.960 --> 00:37:51.220
It attacks your feet.

00:37:51.220 --> 00:37:53.250
So that your nerves
aren't working well.

00:37:53.250 --> 00:37:56.020
You get numb or sometimes
you get pain.

00:37:56.020 --> 00:37:58.320
And the -- the nerves
of the hand, same story.

00:37:58.320 --> 00:38:01.450
One of our participants
was a jazz bass player

00:38:01.450 --> 00:38:04.170
and he had neuropathy in his hands.

00:38:04.170 --> 00:38:07.350
And after about one or two
songs, he -- he had to stop.

00:38:07.350 --> 00:38:09.370
He would turn his back to the
audience and just shake his hands

00:38:09.370 --> 00:38:11.430
out to try to get his
nerves working again

00:38:11.430 --> 00:38:12.840
and then he could play
another song or two.

00:38:12.840 --> 00:38:14.410
Then he'd have to stop.

00:38:14.410 --> 00:38:19.920
He came in to our, uh, research
center, went on a plant based diet

00:38:19.920 --> 00:38:23.630
and a plant based diet,
keeping oils low too,

00:38:23.630 --> 00:38:25.080
what does that do to the cell?

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:29.630
It causes that fat to come out,
the insulin starts working again,

00:38:29.630 --> 00:38:31.090
it brings his blood sugar down,

00:38:31.090 --> 00:38:33.050
suddenly the nerves
aren't being attacked

00:38:33.050 --> 00:38:36.350
by that persistent high blood
sugar and narrowed arteries.

00:38:36.350 --> 00:38:38.720
And after about two or three
months he said, "I can play again."

00:38:38.720 --> 00:38:41.710
And he could play through a
whole set without any problem.

00:38:41.710 --> 00:38:43.180
Two months after that
he came in and said,

00:38:43.180 --> 00:38:45.070
"My erectile dysfunction is gone!"

00:38:45.070 --> 00:38:48.550
So, high fives all the
way around the room.

00:38:48.550 --> 00:38:49.850
Anyway. It's really true.

00:38:49.850 --> 00:38:53.660
You know, that does not happen
by just filling a prescription.

00:38:53.660 --> 00:38:54.960
Now, don't get me wrong.

00:38:54.960 --> 00:38:56.260
Don't fire your doctor.

00:38:56.260 --> 00:38:57.580
And there are times when
medicines are really important

00:38:57.580 --> 00:38:59.010
and sometimes lifesaving.

00:38:59.010 --> 00:39:02.600 position:56%
But if you are not tackling the
cause and the cause relates to diet,

00:39:02.600 --> 00:39:04.670
we just go one arm
tied behind our back.

00:39:04.670 --> 00:39:07.670
OK. So plant based diets, they
improve cholesterol levels.

00:39:07.670 --> 00:39:08.970
They improve body weight.

00:39:08.970 --> 00:39:10.270
They improve blood pressure.

00:39:10.270 --> 00:39:11.970
They improve diabetes.

00:39:11.970 --> 00:39:18.210
And so this is the graphic
that we developed back in 2009

00:39:18.210 --> 00:39:20.520 position:56%
to summarize what a healthy diet is.

00:39:20.520 --> 00:39:21.840
So it's fruits.

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:23.140
It's grains.

00:39:23.140 --> 00:39:24.440
It's vegetables.

00:39:24.440 --> 00:39:25.740
It's legumes.

00:39:25.740 --> 00:39:28.720
And, by the way, we brought
this to the USDA, um, and said,

00:39:28.720 --> 00:39:30.020
